Integrating Claude-Code-Tools into Dopemux – Deep Dive & Implementation Plan

Executive Brief

Overview: The open-source Claude-Code-Tools repository ￼ ￼ by Prasad Chalasani provides a suite of productivity enhancements for AI coding agents (developed for Anthropic’s Claude Code, but broadly applicable). Its features directly align with Dopemux’s goals: tmux-based multiplexing of CLI sessions, orchestrating multiple AI agents, robust safety guardrails, and multi-model (provider) routing. By adopting or mimicking these tools in Dopemux, we can dramatically improve interactive capabilities (e.g. running interactive scripts, multi-agent collaboration), session management, and safety/operations without reinventing the wheel. All components are MIT-licensed ￼, which ensures compatibility with Dopemux’s licensing and allows code reuse or adaptation.

Key Components to Integrate:
  •  tmux-cli (Terminal Automation): Enables an AI agent to control terminal applications programmatically, essentially acting as “Playwright for terminals” ￼. This allows Claude (or any CLI-based agent) to run interactive scripts, use debuggers (pdb/gdb), or even launch another agent instance visibly in a new pane ￼ ￼. Incorporating this in Dopemux would unlock robust multi-agent orchestration and interactive testing workflows.
  •  Session Search & Resume Tools: find-session, find-claude-session, and find-codex-session provide unified search across session transcripts and one-command resume with correct context ￼ ￼. These improve developer productivity by quickly locating past conversations or debugging sessions across projects and agents. Dopemux can integrate a similar “dmx session” system to search and resume sessions across its multi-agent environment.
  •  Safety Hooks & Env Tools: A comprehensive set of safety hooks guard against dangerous operations (file deletion, wildcard git adds, .env exposure, reading huge files, etc.) ￼ ￼. Additionally, env-safe and vault tools handle environment secrets safely – env-safe allows listing or checking env vars without ever revealing sensitive values ￼, and vault provides encrypted backup/sync for .env files using SOPS ￼. These features align with Dopemux’s need for strict guardrails in an AI-driven CLI and secure management of credentials.
  •  Multi-Model Routing (Provider Shims): Functions like kimi(), zai(), dseek() route Claude Code to alternative Anthropic-compatible endpoints (Kimi, Zai, DeepSeek, etc.) by setting endpoint URLs and API keys in a subshell ￼ ￼. This allows seamless switching between models and even concurrent instances each with different LLM backends ￼. Dopemux can offer an integrated provider-routing system so users (or the orchestrator) can easily assign different AI models to different sessions or tasks.

Return on Investment: These features solve real pain points in agentic coding workflows – enabling interactive program control, preserving institutional knowledge via session recall, preventing costly mistakes (like accidental rm or credential leaks), and leveraging multiple AI models effortlessly. By mapping Claude-Code-Tools into Dopemux, we fast-track these capabilities with proven implementations. The highest-impact areas are tmux-cli (for orchestrated multi-agent workflows) and the safety hooks (for trust and reliability). We will prioritize those first, while also integrating session search and env management for completeness. A phased adoption is recommended: first get tmux orchestration and safety basics working, then layer on session search, vault, and provider routing. Overall, the integration elevates Dopemux from a basic tmux TUI to a smart, safe, and flexible AI coding environment, leveraging Claude-Code-Tools’ battle-tested ideas to avoid pitfalls.

Feature Inventory & Mapping to Dopemux

The following table maps each major feature of Claude-Code-Tools to its planned counterpart in Dopemux, outlining its value, intended Dopemux implementation, and notes on effort or risks:

Claude-Code-Tools Feature  Value Proposition  Dopemux Integration (API & Design)  Effort / Risk
tmux-cli (Terminal controller)  Allows an AI agent to programmatically control interactive CLI programs. Enables running scripts that require input, using interactive debuggers, or even Claude-to-Claude conversations in separate visible windows ￼ ￼. Essentially “terminal automation for AI” ￼.  Dopemux: Implement as a dmx-tmux plugin. Provide commands like dmx tmux open <agent> (to spawn a new agent pane), dmx tmux send <pane> "<keystrokes>" (to send input), dmx tmux capture <pane> (to read output). The Dopemux orchestrator (possibly via libtmux) will handle pane management and keystroke injection. Bind hotkeys (e.g. Ctrl-D N for new agent, etc.) for quick use. Make this accessible to the AI agent as well (so an agent in one pane can call a secure API to control another pane).  Effort: Moderate. Dopemux already uses tmux; we can leverage libtmux integration (already under research in Dopemux ￼) to implement this cleanly. Risk: Need to enforce safety (to avoid infinite loops or destructive commands via automation). Also must ensure synchronization (reading output reliably) – might need small delays or expect prompts.
find-session (Unified session search)  Global search through past sessions (Claude and Codex) with one command, yielding an interactive list. Supports multiple agents, projects, and keywords, plus a “smart resume” that uses the right agent CLI to reopen the session ￼. Preserves working directory on resume via shell wrapper ￼. Greatly speeds up retrieving context from prior work.  Dopemux: Provide a dmx session find command that searches across all saved session logs (across Dopemux’s own agent logs, and possibly we can plug in Claude or other agent logs if relevant). Use filters for agent type and project. The UI can be similar rich-text table output showing session metadata (agent, date, branch, snippet) for selection ￼ ￼. On selection, Dopemux calls the appropriate resume command (e.g., for a Claude session use claude -r <id>, for a Dopemux native session maybe dmx resume <id>). Also implement persistent directory restore (store cwd in session metadata and cd to it on resume). Possibly create shell aliases fs (find-session), fcs (find Claude session) for convenience ￼ ￼.  Effort: Moderate. Requires reading and indexing session files (likely JSONL logs) for multiple agent types. Dopemux may need to interface with Claude’s and Codex’s session storage if we want cross-tool search, or just focus on Dopemux’s sessions. Risk: Dealing with different log formats (Claude vs Codex vs Dopemux) and maintaining an up-to-date index. Also, ensuring the resumed session integrates with Dopemux UI (potentially spawning a new pane running the agent in resume mode).
find-claude-session / find-codex-session  Agent-specific session search with interactive UI (previews of last user message, etc.) and direct resume ￼ ￼. Essentially special cases of find-session focusing on one agent type, with convenience wrappers (fcs, fcs-codex). Also handles subtle differences (file paths, metadata) between Claude and Codex logs ￼.  Dopemux: Could be integrated into dmx session find with --agent filters (e.g. --agent claude or --agent codex). However, for familiarity we might also add shortcuts: dmx session find-claude alias or detect automatically if running inside a Claude agent context. The unified tool can handle differences internally (we’ll incorporate logic similar to Claude-Code-Tools to find Claude’s ~/.claude/sessions vs Codex’s ~/.codex/sessions structure ￼). The interactive behavior and options (copy session to file, show path, etc.) will be ported.  Effort: Low incremental once find-session is implemented. Just additional filtering and using the appropriate resume command. Risk: Minimal; just ensuring we don’t break specialized features (like Codex’s session metadata parsing ￼). Possibly need to adjust for any differences in how Dopemux itself might log sessions.
vault (Encrypted env backup)  A unified vault for .env files across projects, using SOPS (which leverages GPG) for encryption ￼. Allows easy backup or sync of environment configs: e.g. vault encrypt to save local .env to a central git repo (like ~/Git/dotenvs), vault decrypt to restore, vault sync to auto-detect direction, plus listing and status ￼. Protects secrets at rest and supports sharing across machines securely.  Dopemux: Introduce a dmx vault command group. We can adopt the same subcommands: dmx vault encrypt (copy and encrypt current project’s .env to central location), dmx vault decrypt (restore latest .env), dmx vault sync (compare timestamps and do the appropriate push/pull), etc. ￼. Use SOPS under the hood – likely require user to have GPG keys set up. The central vault path could default to ~/.dopemux/vault/ or similar (or reuse ~/Git/dotenvs/ convention). Ensure that vault list and vault status show clear info for Dopemux projects. Possibly integrate with Dopemux’s config or project metadata to identify projects.  Effort: Low to medium. The Claude tool likely has a Python implementation we can mimic or call directly (since MIT license). We need to ensure SOPS is installed and maybe provide guidance to user to set up a GPG key. Risk: Mainly user setup complexity (GPG keys, SOPS installation ￼). Also must carefully handle errors (e.g., decrypt when no backup exists, or encryption conflicts). Testing needed to ensure no data loss.
env-safe (Safe .env inspection)  Prevents secret leaks by providing read-only, value-sanitized access to .env content ￼. Supports listing env var keys, checking if a key exists, counting defined vs empty, and validating syntax ￼ – never printing actual values. This works in tandem with safety hooks which completely block direct .env reads ￼. Claude (or Dopemux’s AI agent) can thus be allowed to use env-safe to reason about env configuration (like knowing a key exists or is empty) without exposing credentials ￼.  Dopemux: Provide an dmx env tool (or incorporate into a broader dmx-safe plugin). Subcommands: dmx env list (show all keys, possibly with an indicator for set/empty if --status flag), dmx env check <KEY>, dmx env count, dmx env validate. The implementation can be directly borrowed from Claude-Code-Tools (ensuring that printing values is removed or masked). Additionally, Dopemux’s policy engine will outright block any attempt by an AI to open .env files, funneling them to use dmx env instead – similar to Claude’s approach ￼ ￼. We will document that any env modifications must be done by the human developer (outside the AI agent), not via Dopemux.  Effort: Low. This is mostly a read-only parser for .env files – straightforward to implement or reuse. Risk: Low; just need to ensure the blocking hooks are in place so that the AI cannot bypass and read the file directly. Also, we should ensure dmx env validate is in sync with .env syntax rules.
Claude Code Safety Hooks (Bash, Git, etc.)  A set of global CLI hooks that intercept dangerous commands to prevent accidents ￼. Key protections include: File deletion safety (block raw rm unless directed to safe trash), Git guardrails – e.g. block git add . or --all entirely ￼, require confirmation (“speed bump”) for adding entire directories or committing (first attempt warns, second proceeds) ￼, and block unsafe git checkout that might discard changes. Env file locks – completely disallow reading/writing .env (point user/AI to env-safe instead) ￼. Context limits – refuse reading very large files (>500 lines) to avoid prompt bloat ￼. Force rg over grep for performance ￼. These are installed via a hooks config in ~/.claude/settings.json pointing to scripts in the repo ￼ ￼.  Dopemux: Build a dmx-safe or policy module that implements similar hooks within Dopemux’s command processing pipeline. Since Dopemux controls the shell/commands that the AI executes, we can intercept those commands and apply these rules: e.g., detect an rm command in the AI’s output before execution – block it and replace with a safe alternative or prompt; intercept git add or commit commands and require an explicit confirmation (possibly the agent must output the command twice, or the user must confirm via UI); intercept any attempt to read .env (file read request) and abort it with an explanation, suggesting dmx env list instead. We will enforce using rg by intercepting grep commands and swapping them out or advising the AI accordingly. Technically, Dopemux could integrate these at the shell level or as middleware in the orchestration layer. Additionally, Dopemux might expose a configuration (similar to Claude’s settings.json) for these policies, but they might be on by default for all Dopemux sessions (with perhaps an override for advanced users). We also include any extra hooks from Claude-Code-Tools like notification_hook.sh (could be repurposed to send notifications on long tasks) or subtask state flags if relevant ￼.  Effort: Medium. Need to carefully implement command parsing/monitoring in Dopemux’s execution flow. Dopemux likely already has some policy framework; we should fit into that. Possibly reuse logic from Claude’s hooks scripts (translated to Python if needed, given Dopemux is Python-based). Risk: High importance to get right – an overly aggressive hook could impede normal usage (false positives), whereas a missed hook could allow a dangerous operation. Thorough testing required (e.g., ensure rm -rf is truly blocked, but allow safe deletions when intended, etc.). Also need to maintain ease-of-use – e.g., the “speed bump” approach for git commit should be clear to the user/AI why it’s blocked first time.
Alt-Provider Shell Shims (kimi, zai, dseek functions)  Simple yet powerful approach to multi-model support: by defining shell functions that set ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL and ANTHROPIC_API_KEY (and model names if needed) in a subshell, then invoke claude ￼ ￼. This allows users to spin up Claude Code sessions that actually hit a different backend (Kimi, Zai, DeepSeek, etc.), without changing Claude Code itself. The use of a subshell ensures each session’s env vars don’t bleed into others, enabling concurrent usage of different models ￼. In practice, a user can simply type kimi instead of claude to get an AI coding session on the Kimi model.  Dopemux: Because Dopemux is an orchestrator for multiple agents, we can formalize this capability. Options: (1) Provide a CLI command or flag to launch a new agent specifying the model/provider, e.g. dmx new --provider=kimi or dmx use-model kimi which internally sets up the environment and calls Claude Code with the alternate base URL. (2) In a GUI/TUI context, allow the user to choose the model for a pane from a menu. Under the hood, Dopemux can manage API keys and endpoints (perhaps in a config file or environment variables) for known providers. We might integrate with Dopemux’s ClaudeCodeRouter (it appears Dopemux already has a ClaudeCodeRouterManager to handle alternate endpoints via a local router ￼ ￼). The simplest initial implementation could mimic the shell functions: e.g. dmx kimi simply spawns a Dopemux/Claude instance with the env var overrides, similar to the provided snippet. Over time, a more robust model routing UI can be built (with support for additional providers and dynamic selection per agent).  Effort: Low to start (shell function approach is trivial to implement within Dopemux’s launch commands). Risk: Low. Need to ensure API keys are provided by user securely (maybe via environment or Dopemux config). Also consider that anthropic-compatible models might have different capabilities (context length, etc.); Dopemux’s orchestration should be aware if needed. We should clearly document how to add a new provider function. Over-reliance on environment variables might conflict if a user runs multiple models in one shell without using subshell – but our implementation will isolate them properly.

